title.narrative: MATERNAL AND CHILD NUTRITION IN EMERGENCIES

description.narrative: Girls and boys under five years old and caregivers affected by humanitarian crises have increased and timely access to quality nutrition services in line with UNICEF Core Commitments for Children in Humanitarian Action (CCC), which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: New Element

title.narrative: Girls and boys under five years old and caregivers affected by humanitarian crises have increased and timely access to qualitynutrition services in line with UNICEF Core Commitments for Children in Humanitarian Action (CCC)

description.narrative: UNICEF contributed to equitable access to timely and quality nutrition services in humanitarian crises, by supporting preparedness and implementation of life-saving essential nutrition services targeting women and children at-risk of food and nutrition insecurity. UNICEF facilitated treatment of 44,335;children under the age of five with severe acute malnutrition (SAM) and 404,561;pregnant women/caregivers of children 0-23 months (above 100;per cent of annual target) were reached with counselling services on adequate infant and young child feeding (IYCF). The existence of a functional coordination and timely emergency preparedness plan contributed significantly to timely and quality nutrition response in emergencies.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/12/2021
